<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Retirees in Sri Lanka | Visa Guide 2026"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees in Sri Lanka. Compare international plans with medical evacuation, pre-existing coverage, and age 65+ acceptance in this tropical island paradise."
  headline="Health Insurance for Retirees in Sri Lanka"
  subheadline="Your guide to comprehensive health coverage on the Indian Ocean's emerald island"
  heroImage="/images/countries/default-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Retiree Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <section id="overview">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Sri Lanka offers retirees tropical beauty, ancient culture, and remarkable affordability on a compact, easily navigable island. From palm-fringed beaches to misty tea plantations to ancient Buddhist temples, this teardrop-shaped island delivers diverse experiences within a few hours' travel. English is widely spoken, making daily life accessible for foreign retirees.
    </p>
    <p>
      Healthcare in Sri Lanka is adequate for routine needs, with private hospitals in Colombo providing reasonable care. Complex conditions typically require evacuation to Singapore, Bangkok, or India. The country's "My Dream Home" visa program specifically targets retirees, offering straightforward long-term residence for those meeting modest requirements.
    </p>
    <p>
      This guide covers Sri Lanka's visa options for retirees, healthcare realities, insurance strategies, and cost planning for retirement on this increasingly popular tropical island.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="why-sri-lanka">
    <h2>Why Retirees Choose Sri Lanka</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Compact diversity</strong> packs beaches, mountains, wildlife, and culture into an island smaller than Ireland. Morning on the beach, afternoon in the hills—Sri Lanka's small size makes everything accessible without exhausting travel. You can experience the entire country without committing to one location.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Affordability</strong> enables comfortable retirement on modest income. A couple can live well for $1,200-1,800/month including health insurance. Quality accommodation, domestic help, and services are remarkably affordable by Western standards.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>English widely spoken</strong> removes the language barrier common in Asian destinations. English is an official language, used in government, education, and business. Healthcare, services, and daily life work smoothly in English throughout the country.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Beautiful beaches</strong> along the south and east coasts offer tropical living without Thai-level tourism crowds. Galle, Mirissa, Unawatuna, and Trincomalee provide different beach vibes from colonial charm to surf culture to quiet relaxation.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Hill country escape</strong> in Kandy, Ella, and Nuwara Eliya provides cool climate alternatives to coastal heat. Tea plantations, waterfalls, and misty mountain scenery offer contrast to beach life. Many retirees split time between coast and hills seasonally.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Buddhist culture</strong> creates a generally peaceful, tolerant atmosphere. Ancient temples, meditation retreats, and spiritual heritage appeal to retirees seeking meaning beyond beaches. The cultural depth provides ongoing exploration and engagement.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="visa-options">
    <h2>Visa Options</h2>
    <p>
      Sri Lanka offers a dedicated retiree visa program plus other options for long-term stays. The "My Dream Home" visa specifically targets foreign retirees.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>My Dream Home visa</strong> is Sri Lanka's retirement visa, available to those 55+ with proof of pension/retirement income ($1,500/month minimum) or substantial savings. Initial visa is for 2 years, renewable. Requires health insurance and clean criminal record. This is the recommended pathway for serious retirees.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tourist visa extensions:</strong> Initial tourist visa (30 days) can be extended to 90 days, then further extended to 6 months with application to the Department of Immigration. Some retirees use this approach for extended stays without committing to residence. Less stable than dedicated retirement visa.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Resident Guest visa:</strong> For those with business interests or specific purposes, this visa allows stays up to 5 years. Requires evidence of funds ($15,000+ in Sri Lankan bank) and specific purpose. More complex than retirement visa.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Health insurance requirement:</strong> The My Dream Home visa requires proof of health insurance. International coverage meeting minimum requirements satisfies this obligation. Given Sri Lanka's healthcare limitations, comprehensive coverage with evacuation is strongly recommended regardless of legal requirements.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Application process:</strong> My Dream Home applications go through the Department of Immigration and Emigration. Required documents include passport, proof of income/savings, health insurance, criminal record check, and medical certificate. Processing takes 1-2 months typically.
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Quotes for Sri Lanka Coverage"
    description="Compare international health insurance plans with strong regional evacuation networks—essential for comprehensive protection in Sri Lanka."
    buttonText="Compare Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <section id="insurance-options">
    <h2>Insurance Options for Retirees</h2>
    <p>
      Sri Lanka's healthcare handles routine needs but has limitations for complex conditions. Insurance strategy should prioritize evacuation coverage to Singapore, Bangkok, or India's major hospitals.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>International health insurance</strong> provides access to Colombo's best private hospitals with direct billing, comprehensive regional coverage including evacuation destinations, and security for complex conditions. This is the recommended foundation for foreign retirees.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Evacuation coverage</strong> is particularly important. Colombo's private hospitals handle routine care, but complex cardiac surgery, advanced oncology, and specialized procedures typically require evacuation. Singapore (4 hours), Bangkok (3.5 hours), and Chennai/Mumbai (1-2 hours) are common destinations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Sri Lankan private insurance</strong> from providers like Ceylinco and AIA Sri Lanka offers local coverage at low cost ($30-80/month). These plans provide access to private hospitals but limited international portability. Useful supplement but not sufficient as primary coverage.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Public healthcare:</strong> Sri Lanka has universal public healthcare with reasonable quality for a developing country. Government hospitals are free but crowded with long waits. Useful as backup but not recommended as primary care for foreign retirees.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Combination strategies:</strong> Sri Lankan private insurance for convenient local clinic access plus international coverage for complex care and evacuation provides comprehensive protection at reasonable total cost.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="recommended-providers">
    <h2>Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
    <p>
      These international insurers provide comprehensive coverage for Sri Lanka retirees with established regional evacuation networks to Singapore, Bangkok, and India.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Cigna Global</strong> offers extensive coverage with established evacuation protocols to regional centers. Their network includes Singapore and Bangkok hospitals—key evacuation destinations. Moratorium underwriting helps those with pre-existing conditions.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Aetna International</strong> provides unlimited evacuation coverage and strong Asia-Pacific regional plans. Their network includes comprehensive coverage in Sri Lanka's evacuation destinations—Singapore, Thailand, and India.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>IMG Global</strong> provides competitive pricing for budget-conscious retirees. Their regional network covers evacuation to Singapore and Bangkok when needed.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers no maximum entry age for existing members and comprehensive coverage. Strong choice for British expats given historical Sri Lanka connections and continuity of UK healthcare access.
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Retiree Plans for Sri Lanka"
