  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Sri Lanka's healthcare is adequate for routine needs—better than many developing countries—but limited for complex conditions. Understanding the system helps set realistic expectations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Colombo private hospitals</strong> including Lanka Hospitals, Nawaloka, and Asiri Hospitals provide reasonable care for routine surgery, common conditions, and basic emergencies. Facilities are adequate, and many doctors trained abroad. Direct billing with international insurers is common at major facilities.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Outside Colombo,</strong> capabilities diminish. Galle and Kandy have private hospitals adequate for basic care, but serious conditions require Colombo or evacuation. Beach and hill country locations are further from comprehensive medical facilities.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Common evacuation scenarios</strong> include complex cardiac procedures, advanced oncology, specialized surgery, and rare conditions. Singapore (4 hours by air) offers world-class care. Bangkok (3.5 hours) is another excellent option. Chennai and Mumbai (1-2 hours) provide capable Indian private hospitals at lower cost.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>English availability:</strong> Excellent throughout Sri Lankan healthcare. Most doctors speak English well, and hospital communication works smoothly for English speakers. This is a significant advantage over many Asian destinations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Pharmacies are abundant and medications affordable. Most common medications are available. Some specialty medications may require import from India or elsewhere. Quality is generally good from reputable pharmacies.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      Sri Lanka offers excellent value—affordable tropical living with reasonable infrastructure. Currency is the Sri Lankan rupee (LKR), which has been volatile in recent years—check current conditions.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> for comfortable retirement with comprehensive health coverage typically ranges from $1,200-2,000 depending on location and lifestyle. Colombo comfortable retirement runs $1,500-2,000; south coast beaches $1,300-1,800; hill country $1,100-1,600.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare cost value:</strong> Sri Lanka provides adequate local care at low cost. International insurance ($250-550/month) ensures access to the best local facilities plus evacuation to Singapore or Bangkok when needed. The combination provides good protection at reasonable total cost.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Currency considerations:</strong> The Sri Lankan rupee has experienced significant volatility, including a major economic crisis in 2022. When the rupee weakens, your dollar income buys more—but volatility creates uncertainty. Monitor economic conditions and maintain some hard currency reserves.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Domestic help:</strong> Very affordable—full-time household help costs $100-200/month. Cook, cleaner, driver services are accessible to middle-class retirees. This enhances quality of life significantly.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Sri Lanka stable after the 2022 economic crisis?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Conditions have improved since 2022's crisis, but the situation bears monitoring. Tourism has recovered, and daily life for expats is largely normal. However, currency volatility and periodic shortages may occur. Research current conditions before committing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Sri Lanka safe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Generally yes—the civil war ended in 2009, and tourist areas are safe. Petty crime exists but violent crime against foreigners is rare. Occasional political protests occur but rarely affect tourist/expat areas. Most retirees report feeling secure.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How far is serious medical care?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Colombo handles routine care. For complex conditions: Singapore is 4 hours by air, Bangkok 3.5 hours, Chennai/Mumbai 1-2 hours. From south coast beaches, Colombo is 2-3 hours by road. Your insurance coordinates evacuations when needed.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What's the climate like?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Tropical—hot and humid on coasts year-round. Hill country (Kandy, Ella) is cooler and pleasant. Monsoon patterns vary by coast: southwest monsoon May-September affects south/west coasts; northeast monsoon October-January affects east coast. Choose location based on preferred season.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How does Sri Lanka compare to Thailand for retirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Sri Lanka is cheaper and less developed than Thailand. Healthcare is weaker (Thailand has excellent hospitals). Sri Lanka is more compact and culturally distinct. Thailand has better infrastructure and established expat services. Sri Lanka suits those wanting authentic, affordable experience; Thailand suits those prioritizing comfort and healthcare.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is the My Dream Home visa process difficult?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Relatively straightforward compared to many countries. Requirements (55+, $1,500/month income, insurance) are reasonable. Processing takes 1-2 months typically. Bureaucracy exists but isn't prohibitive. Using a local agent helps navigate requirements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your Sri Lanka Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers with regional evacuation networks. Coverage that provides security on this beautiful tropical island."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />
</PageShell>
